The passive serves on occasion as the passive of the middle as well
							as the passive of the active. bia/zomai,
							I suffer violence (I am forced);
							a)fairou=mai, I am robbed;
							h(|re/qhn, I was chosen.
							Not so, however, in Homer.

deo/mena/ e)sti = oi(=a/ e)sti dei=sqai, comp. XEN. Oec. 7.21. prosh=ko/n e)sti, It is becoming;
							prosh/kei, It becomes.
							ai)sqano/menos, PLATO, Theaet. 160A = ai)sqhth/s, Ibid. 160 D.

ti/ ou)=n ou) diw/komen w(s ta/xista;
							XEN. Cyr. 4.1.11; Why, then, do we not pursue with all
								speed?

The present tense of a number of verbs that involve unity of
							character or persistence of result, is often translated by the
							English perfect. nikw=, I am
								victorious, I have conquered;
							h(/kw, I am here, I have arrived;
							oi)/xomai, I am off, I am gone;
							a)kou/w, I hear or
							have heard;
							punqa/nomai, I learn or
							have learned.
							ste/romai, I am deprived,
							and so all verbs of privation.

