The perfect is largely used in Greek for the maintenance of the
							result, and the translation into English is often present: ke/klhmai, my name is;
							me/mnhmai, I have recalled, I
								remember;
							ke/kthmai, I have got, I own;
							ei)/qismai, I have made it my
								rule, I am accustomed.

ei) ga\r prolei/yeis m(e) . . ., oi)xo/mesqa (oi)xo/mesqa is a
							practical perfect), EUR. Or. 304-5;
							If thou shalt abandon me, I am gone (lost).

